:::summary
William Shakespeare (1564–1616) is the most celebrated writer in the English language and widely regarded as the greatest dramatist in world literature. In 37 plays and 154 sonnets, he explored the full range of human experience — love, ambition, jealousy, grief, redemption, and mortality — with a mastery of language and psychological insight that has never been surpassed. His works have been translated into every major language and performed continuously for over four centuries.
:::

